############### STEP 4: Statistical analysis of amplitude effects ###############
# This script runs inferential statistics on the extracted factors.
# Author: Florian Scharf, florian.scharf@uni-muenster.de and Andreas Widmann, widmann@uni-leipzig.de

# empty workspace
rm(list=ls())

## Load necessary packages 
if(!require(afex)) install.packages("afex")
## Lade ntiges Paket: afex
## Lade ntiges Paket: lme4
## Lade ntiges Paket: Matrix
## Registered S3 methods overwritten by 'car':
##   method                          from
##   influence.merMod                lme4
##   cooks.distance.influence.merMod lme4

##   dfbetas.influence.merMod        lme4
## ************
## Welcome to afex. For support visit: http://afex.singmann.science/
## - Functions for ANOVAs: aov_car(), aov_ez(), and aov_4()
## - Methods for calculating p-values with mixed(): 'KR', 'S', 'LRT', and 'PB'
## - 'afex_aov' and 'mixed' objects can be passed to emmeans() for follow-up tests
## - NEWS: library('emmeans') now needs to be called explicitly!

## Attache Paket: 'afex'
## Das folgende Objekt ist maskiert 'package:lme4':
## 
##     lmer
if(!require(BayesFactor)) install.packages("BayesFactor")
## Lade ntiges Paket: BayesFactor
## Lade ntiges Paket: coda
## ************
## Welcome to BayesFactor 0.9.12-4.2. If you have questions, please contact Richard Morey (richarddmorey@gmail.com).

if(!require(bayestestR)) install.packages("bayestestR")
## Lade ntiges Paket: bayestestR
library(afex)
library(psych)
library(BayesFactor)
library(bayestestR)
library(ggplot2)
## 
## Attache Paket: 'ggplot2'
## Die folgenden Objekte sind maskiert von 'package:psych':
## 
##     %+%, alpha
## Load the data from both PCAs and put the results into separate objects
load("results/02bc_rotation_score/rotfit_ad23_geomin0.01.Rdata",  temp_env <- new.env())
adPCA <- as.list.environment(temp_env)
load("results/02bc_rotation_score/rotfit_ch21_geomin0.01.Rdata",  temp_env <- new.env())
chPCA <- as.list.environment(temp_env)

## Compute the dependent variables for statistical analyses 

## Adult PCA
# Compute unstandardized factor loadings
adPCA$rotFit$loadings_unstd <- adPCA$rotFit$loadings * adPCA$rotFit$varSD
# Compute the peak loading for each factor
adPCA$peak_loadings <- apply(adPCA$rotFit$loadings_unstd, MARGIN = 2, FUN = max)
# Multiply peak loadings with factor scores
adPCA$scores[,-c(1:4)] = as.matrix(adPCA$scores[,-c(1:4)]) %*% diag(adPCA$peak_loadings)

## Child PCA
# Compute unstandardized factor loadings
chPCA$rotFit$loadings_unstd <- chPCA$rotFit$loadings * chPCA$rotFit$varSD
# Compute the peak loading for each factor
chPCA$peak_loadings <- apply(chPCA$rotFit$loadings_unstd, MARGIN = 2, FUN = max)
# Multiply peak loadings with factor scores
chPCA$scores[,-c(1:4)] = as.matrix(chPCA$scores[,-c(1:4)]) %*% diag(chPCA$peak_loadings)

## Relable the factors which we labeled in the text.
# Based on all results we labeled the factors as follows:
## Adults
# "Factor 1" LDN
# "Factor 2" P2
# "Factor 3" late P3a
# "Factor 5" early P3a

## Children
# "Factor 1" LDN
# "Factor 2" P2
# "Factor 5" late P3a
# "Factor 6" earlyP3a


# Which factors need to be relabeled?
highlighted_FA_ad <- names(adPCA$scores) %in% paste0("X", c(1,2,3,5))
highlighted_FA_ch <- names(chPCA$scores) %in% paste0("X", c(1,2,5,6))

# Rename the respective columns
names(adPCA$scores)[highlighted_FA_ad] <- c("LDN", "P2", "lP3a", "eP3a")
names(chPCA$scores)[highlighted_FA_ch] <- c("LDN", "P2", "lP3a", "eP3a")

# Create a new data set containing both groups and only the relevant data
scores = rbind(chPCA$scores[, c("group", "cond", "subj", "chan", "P2", "eP3a", "lP3a", "LDN")], adPCA$scores[, c("group", "cond", "subj", "chan", "P2", "eP3a", "lP3a", "LDN")])

# Compute difference scores for plotting purposes
scores_diff = scores[scores$cond == "nov",]
scores_diff[, 5:8] = scores[scores$cond == "nov", 5:8] - scores[scores$cond == "sta", 5:8]
scores_diff[, "cond"] = "nov-sta"

# Export final file, if you prefer, you can analyze the scores in a different
# software such as JASP or SPSS.
write.csv(scores, file = "results/04_stat_amplitudes/final_scores.csv")

########### Factorwise-statistical analysis ###########
##### Factor P2 #####

# Descriptive Statistics
describeBy(P2 ~ cond + group, data = scores[scores$chan == "Cz",], mat = TRUE, digits = 3)
##     item group1 group2 vars  n   mean    sd median trimmed   mad    min    max
## X11    1    sta     ad    1 32  3.548 2.001  3.497   3.490 1.535 -0.493  9.234

## X13 12.374 0.028   -0.604 0.535
## X14 24.653 0.110   -0.123 0.916
# Frequentist ANOVA
fit <- aov_ez(data = scores[scores$chan == "Cz",], dv = "P2", id = "subj", between = "group", within = "cond", type = 3)
## Contrasts set to contr.sum for the following variables: group
fit
## Anova Table (Type 3 tests)
## 
## Response: P2
##       Effect    df   MSE          F  ges p.value
## 1      group 1, 62 23.40     4.53 * .054    .037
## 2       cond 1, 62  6.54 134.21 *** .321   <.001
## 3 group:cond 1, 62  6.54  88.41 *** .237   <.001
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '+' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Bayes ANOVA
res = anovaBF(P2 ~ (cond * group) + subj, data = scores, 
              whichRandom = "subj", 
              whichModels = "withmain", 
              rscaleRandom = "nuisance", 
              rscaleFixed = "medium", iterations = 10000)
sort(res)
## Bayes factor analysis
## --------------
## [1] group + subj                     : 0.5698373    1.05%
## [2] group + cond + subj              : 2.06117e+35  3.05%
## [3] cond + subj                      : 3.51681e+35  1.63%
## [4] group + cond + group:cond + subj : 6.434072e+80 4.36%
## 
## Against denominator:
##   P2 ~ subj 
## ---
## Bayes factor type: BFlinearModel, JZS
bayesfactor_inclusion(res, match_models = TRUE)
## Inclusion Bayes Factors (Model Averaged)
## 
##            P(prior) P(posterior) Inclusion BF
## subj           1.00         1.00             
## group          0.40     3.20e-46        0.586
## cond           0.40     8.67e-46       > 1000
## cond:group     0.20         1.00       > 1000
## 
## * Compared among: matched models only
## *    Priors odds: uniform-equal
# Frequentist Pairwise comparisons:
#  nov vs. sta 
#  for Adults
t.test(scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "nov",]$P2, 
scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "sta",]$P2, 
paired = TRUE)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "nov", ]$P2 and scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "sta", ]$P2

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.1986834  2.1711848
## sample estimates:
## mean of the differences 
##               0.9862507
#  for Children
t.test(scores[scores$group == "ch" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "nov",]$P2, 
       scores[scores$group == "ch" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "sta",]$P2, 
       paired = TRUE)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  scores[scores$group == "ch" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "nov", ]$P2 and scores[scores$group == "ch" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "sta", ]$P2
## t = 13.697, df = 31, p-value = 1.084e-14
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   8.07400 10.89911
## sample estimates:
## mean of the differences 
##                9.486554
# Bayesian Pairwise comparisons:
#  nov vs. sta 
#  for Adults
ttestBF(scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "nov",]$P2, 
        scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "sta",]$P2, 
        paired = TRUE)
## Bayes factor analysis

        scores[scores$group == "ch" & scores$chan == "Cz" & scores$cond == "sta",]$P2, 
        paired = TRUE)

fit
## Anova Table (Type 3 tests)
## 
## Response: LDN
##       Effect    df  MSE          F  ges p.value
## 1      group 1, 62 8.47 107.40 *** .525   <.001
## 2       cond 1, 62 4.78  27.95 *** .140   <.001
## 3 group:cond 1, 62 4.78   10.17 ** .056    .002
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '+' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Bayes ANOVA
res = anovaBF(LDN ~ (cond * group) + subj, data = scores, 
              whichRandom = "subj", 
              whichModels = "withmain", 
              rscaleRandom = "nuisance", 
              rscaleFixed = "medium", iterations = 10000)
sort(res)
## Bayes factor analysis
## --------------
## [1] cond + subj                      : 0.04507467 0.82%
## [2] group + cond + subj              : 3073161    1.89%
## [3] group + subj                     : 70298507   2.56%
## [4] group + cond + group:cond + subj : 110770582  1.65%
## 
## Against denominator:
##   LDN ~ subj 
## ---
## Bayes factor type: BFlinearModel, JZS
bayesfactor_inclusion(res, match_models = TRUE)

# Frequentist Pairwise comparisons:
#  nov vs. sta 
#  for Adults
t.test(scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "F4" & scores$cond == "nov",]$LDN, 
       scores[scores$group == "ad" & scores$chan == "F4" & scores$cond == "sta",]$LDN, 
       paired = TRUE)

        paired = TRUE)
